To define a tool schema for Claude, create a JSON schema for your tool's `input_schema`. The schema uses standard JSON Schema format with some limitations (see [JSON Schema limitations](/docs/en/build-with-claude/structured-outputs#json-schema-limitations)). 

Here's a basic example of a JSON schema:

```json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "name": {"type": "string"},
    "age": {"type": "integer"}
  },
  "required": ["name", "age"]
}
```

This schema defines an object with two properties: `name` and `age`. Both properties are required and must be of type string and integer, respectively.

To make Claude return citations for its answers, you need to enable citations on the documents you provide to Claude. Currently, citations must be enabled on all or none of the documents within a request.

Here's an example of how to enable citations on a document:

```json
{
  "type": "document",
  "source": {
    "type": "text",
    "media_type": "text/plain",
    "data": "The grass is green. The sky is blue."
  },
  "title": "My Document",
  "context": "This is a trustworthy document.",
  "citations": {"enabled": true}
}
```

You can also use the CLI or Python client to enable citations. Here's an example using the Python client:

```python
import anthropic

client = anthropic.Anthropic()

response = client.messages.create(
    model="claude-opus-4-7",
    max_tokens=1024,
    messages=[
        {
            "role": "user",
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "document",
                    "source": {
                        "type": "text",
                        "media_type": "text/plain",
                        "data": "The grass is green. The sky is blue."
                    },
                    "title": "My Document",
                    "context": "This is a trustworthy document.",
                    "citations": {"enabled": true}
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
)
```

Note that only text citations are currently supported, and image citations are not yet possible.

You can poll for the status of the batch and retrieve results when processing has ended for all requests. The results are available in a `.jsonl` file specified in the `resultsURL` field of the Message Batch object. 

To check the status of a batch, you can use the `retrieve` method of the `beta.messages.batches` endpoint, which returns the Message Batch object. You can then check the `processingStatus` field to determine the status of the batch.

Here's an example in PHP:

```php
<?php

require_once dirname(__DIR__) . '/vendor/autoload.php';

$client = new Client(apiKey: 'my-anthropic-api-key');

$betaMessageBatch = $client->beta->messages->batches->retrieve(
  'message_batch_id', betas: ['message-batches-2024-09-24']
);

if ($betaMessageBatch->processingStatus == 'succeeded') {
    // Processing has ended and results are available
    $resultsURL = $betaMessageBatch->resultsURL;
    // Download the results from the URL
} elseif ($betaMessageBatch->processingStatus == 'failed') {
    // Processing has ended and there were errors
    // Check the requestCounts field to see which requests failed
} else {
    // Processing is still in progress
    // You can poll the endpoint again to check the status
}
```

Note that the results in the file are not guaranteed to be in the same order as the requests. You can use the `custom_id` field to match results to requests.

The MCP connector is a feature in the Claude API that enables you to connect to remote Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers directly from the Messages API without a separate MCP client [1][2]. This allows you to access MCP tools and data sources through a standardized protocol.

To use the MCP connector, you need to include the MCP server definition (`mcp_servers` array) and the MCP toolset (`tools` array) in your API request [3]. The MCP server definition specifies the connection details, such as the URL and authentication token, while the MCP toolset configures which tools to enable and how to configure them.

Here's an example of how to use the MCP connector in your API request:

```json
{
  "model": "claude-opus-4-7",
  "max_tokens": 1000,
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Use tools from both mcp-server-1 and mcp-server-2 to complete this task"
    }
  ],
  "mcp_servers": [
    {
      "type": "url",
      "url": "https://mcp.example1.com/sse",
      "name": "mcp-server-1",
      "authorization_token": "TOKEN1"
    },
    {
      "type": "url",
      "url": "https://mcp.example2.com/sse",
      "name": "mcp-server-2",
      "authorization_token": "TOKEN2"
    }
  ],
  "tools": [
    {
      "type": "mcp_toolset",
      "mcp_server_name": "mcp-server-1"
    },
    {
      "type": "mcp_toolset",
      "mcp_server_name": "mcp-server-2",
      "default_config": {
        "defer_loading": true
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

Note that the MCP connector requires the beta header `"anthropic-beta": "mcp-client-2025-11-20"` and is not eligible for Zero Data Retention (ZDR) [2].
